sities, and government offices, Gustav Cederlöf retells the history of the Cuban Revolution as one of profound environmental and infrastructural change. In doing so, he opens up new questions about energy transitions, their politics, and the conditions of a socially just low-carbon future. The Cuban experience shows how a society can transform itself while rapidly cutting carbon emissions in the search for sustainability.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCarbon dioxide mitigationxEconomic aspectszCuba. 0aEnergy conservationzCuba. 0aEnergy policyzCuba. 0aEnergy transitionxPolitical aspectszCuba. 0aGeopoliticszCuba. 0aInfrastructure (Economics)zCuba. 7aNATURE / Environmental Conservation & Protection.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079134140uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520393141?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520393141423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520393141/original  a978-3-11-079134-1  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_EMB  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles